1. INTRO TO STATISTICAL SCIENCES

1.1 Empirical Studies and Statistical Sciences

Definition:
Statistical Sciences are concerned with all aspects of empirical studies including formulating the problem, planning the experiment, collecting the data, analysing the data, and making conclusions.
An empirical student is one in which we learn by observation or experiment.

Aspects of Empirical Study:

  • problem formulation
  • planning of an experiment
  • data collection
  • analysis of the data
  • conclusions

Definition:
A population is a collection of units
A process is a mechanism by which units are produced over some period of time.
Variates are characteristics of the units represented by letters such as x, y, z.

Examples of Variates

  • Continuous quantities, ex. blood pressure
  • Discrete quantities , ex. presence/absence of a disease
  • Categorial quantities, ex. hair color
  • Ordinary variates: categorical where an ordering is implied. ex. agree/neutral/disagree
  • Complex, ex. open-ended responses

Definition:
An Attribute of a population or process is a function of a variate which is defined for all units in it.
eg. proportion and average

1.2 Data Collection

Approaches to Data Collection

  • Sample Survey:info about a finite group/representation
  • Experiments: impose treatments
  • Observational studies: don’t impose treatments
    • The above two both need to have randomization. In observational studies, this is achieved by randomly selecting. But is experiments, such condition is often met by random assignment.

Why is randomization important?

  • It helps to eliminate bias
  • It helps guard against confounding factors affecting the results.
  • It gives us power to infer our results to the entire population.

1.3 Data Summaries

Summarizing Numerical Data

  • Measure of Location
    • Sample mean (aka sample average)
    • Sample median (aka middle value/ 50th percentile)
      -Sample Mode: the value that appears most frequently.
  • Measure of Variability or Dispersion
    • Sample variance/ Sample standard deviation
    • Range=
    • Interquartile Range:
    • the five number summary of a data set consists of 1) smallest observation; 2) the lower quartile; 3) median; 4) the upper quartile; 5) largest observation.
  • Measure of Shape
    • Sample skewness
    • Sample kurtosis

Skewness measures the degree of symmetry:

  • Negative skewed : mean < median , long tail on the left
  • Positive skewed : mean > median, long tail on the right
  • Symmetric: mean == median

Kurtosis measures the heaviness of the tails and the peakedness of the distribution (relative to the normal).

  • greater than 3 : heavier tails + more peaked center compared to the normal (eg. T-distribution)
  • less than 3 : lighter tails + less peaked center compared to the normal (eg. Uniform)
    Note that R gives the value relative to 3.

The Empirical Rule

if the data are unimodal and roughly symmetric, then

  • Approximately 68% of the data lie within one standard deviation of the mean.
  • Approximately 95% of the data lie within two standard deviation of the mean.
  • Approximately 99.7% of the data lie within three standard deviation of the mean.

1.4 Probability Distributions and Statistical Models

Why use a statistical model?

  • When questions are formulated in terms of parameters of the model.
  • The variate values vary so random variables can describe.
  • Empirical studies usually involve some degree of UNCERTAINTY, and probability is used to quantify it.
  • Procedures are often formulated in terms of models.
  • Models allow us to characterize processes ad to simulate them via experiments.

Responsive V.S. Explanatory Variates

The explanatory variates are to partially explain or determine the distribution of responsive variates.

  • ex. 1718 men were categorized according to 100 coffee/month. and whether they suffered from CHD.
    • 2 categorial variates.
    • We’re interested in whether there is a relation
    • In this case, coffee consumption is an explanatory variate and presence of CHD is a responsive variate

1.5 Data Analysis and Statistical Inference

Data Analysis and Statistical Interface

  • We collect data to increase our knowledge or as a basis for decision making
  • Proper analysis is crucial, and depends on how the data is collected
  • Descriptive statistics and Statistical Inference
    • Descriptive statistics is the portrayal of data to show features or attributes. The goal is to find interesting patterns.
    • Statistical Inference: When data is used for general conclusions.
      • Inductive reasoning: from specific to general
      • Deductive reasoning: use axions (general results) to prove theorems

Methods of Statistical Inference

  • Estimation problem: We are interested in estimating one or more attributes.
    • eg. Estimate the proposition of Ontario residence aged 14-20 who smokes.
  • Hypothesis testing Problem
    • eg. Is it true that in 14-20 group a higher proportion of female than male smoke?
  • Prediction Problem:
    • eg. Based on a clinic trial, how much an individual’s blood pressure will drop for a given dosage of a drug?
  • In the statistical analysis, we use both descriptive statistics and formal methods of statistical inference.

2.6 Checking the Model

  • A typical model has probability density function if the variate Y is continuous, or probability function if Y is discrete, where is (possibly) a vector of parameter values. It is important to check that the model adequately represents the variability in Y.
  • This can be done by comparing the model with the observed data .
  • The model should represent the relative frequency of sets of y-values in large samples.
  • A fundamental check of the model then is to compare the observed frequencies based on the data with the expected frequencies calculated using probabilities from assumed model.

Graphical Checks of Models

  1. Probability Density Function
    • The first graphical method is to superimpose the probability density function of the proposed model on the relative frequency histogram of the data.
    • The drawback of this technique is that the intervals for the relative frequency histogram must be chosen.
  2. Empirical CDF
    • A second graphical method which can be used to check the fit of a model is to plot the empirical cumulative distribution function
    • If the graphs of the two functions differ a great deal, this would suggest that the proposed model is a poor fit to the data. Systematic departures may also suggest a better model for the data.

Checking Gaussian Model

What are we looking for?

  • We should not expect a perfect fit
  • Systematic departure from the theoretical quantities.
  • Outliers
  • There is nothing out of the ordinary i the previous plots

Normal qqplots

  • To compare an empirical c.d.f. with a Normal or Gaussian c.d.f. more easily, we can use a graphic technique called a qqplot.

  • We expect the empirical cumulative distribution function and the cumulative distribution for a Gaussian random variable to agree if a Gaussian model is appropriate for the data as we saw

    • The basic idea is that the plot will be approximately a straight line if a Normal model fits the data.

  • We plot the data

    • this should be approximately a straight line if the data are well modeled by a gaussian distribution.

  • Comparing Quantiles

    • again, we are not looking for perfect match but agreement or systematic departure from the theoretical quantities.
    • we will be able to pick up skewness, thick or thin tail behaviors.

  • Things to look for in a Normal QQ Plot:

    • Stylized S shape: Thin tails - Uniform distribution


- U-shape: Positively/right skewed


- Chair shape: Thick tails - T-distribution

3.PLANNING AND CONDUCTING EMPIRICAL STUDIES

3.1 Empirical Studies

PPDAC

  • PPDAC is designed to emphasize the statistical aspects of empirical studies.
    • Problem: a clear statement of the study’s objectives, usually involving one or more questions
    • Plan: the procedures used to carry out the study including how we will collect the data.
    • Data: the physical collection of the data, as described in the Plan.
    • Analysis: the analysis of the data collected in light of the Problem and the Plan.
    • Conclusion: The conclusions that are drawn about the Problem and their limitations.

3.2 The steps of PPADC

The problem

  • the elements of the problem address questions starting with “What”
  • What groups of things or people do we want to draw conclusions about - Target Population.
  • What Variates need to be defined?
  • What is/are the question(s) that we are trying to answer here?
  • What conclusions are we trying to draw?
  • Question of interest:
    • Questions of interest usually relate to attributes of the target population
    • For example, does taking a certain type of drug reduce the incidence of a certain type of iillness?
    • We usually cannot calculate the exact attributes of interest directly because we are only able to examine a sample of the units in the target population.
    • We may not even be able to examine any units for ethical reasons, and thus may be forced to carry out clinical trials using mice. here *The study population is not a subset of the target population。

The plan

  • The purpose of the Plan step is to decide what units need to be examined.
  • The plan depends on the Problem step
    • Study units are usually elements of the target population.

Definitions:
The study unit are those available to be included in the study.
The Sampling protocol is the procedure used to select a sample of units from the student population.

  • Random sampling can be difficult and expensive, in practice often times.
  • Sometimes we are forced to “take what we can get”

The plan: Source of errors

Definitions

  • If the attributes in the study population differ from the attributes in the target population then the difference is called study error.
  • If the attributes in the sample differ from the attributes in the study population the difference is called sample error.
  • If the measured value and the true value of a variate are not identical the difference is called measurement error.

  • Fore an empirical study, the Plan should indicate the study population, the sampling protocol, the variates to be measured and the quality of the measurement systems.

4. ESTIMATION

4.1 Statistical Models and Estimation

  • In statistical estimation we use two models:
    1. A model which describes the variability in the variate(s) of interest in the population or process being studied.
    2. A model which takes in to account how the data were collected and which is constructed in conjunction with the model in (1).
  • We use the two models to develop methods for estimating the unknown attributes and to determine the uncertainty in the estimates.
  • The unknown attributes are usually represented by

Central Limit Theorem

The Central Limit Theorem states:

  1. If the parent population is Normal(Gaussian), then the distribution of the sample mean will be Normal
  2. If the parent population is not Normal(Gaussian), then the distribution of the sample mean will be approximately Normal for large n.

Good rule of thumb: sample sizes of at least 30 will do.

Guidelines for Interpreting Likelihood intervals

  • Values of inside a 10% likelihood interval are plausible values of in light of the observed data
  • Values of inside a 50% likelihood interval are very plausible values of in light of the observed data
  • Values of outside a 10% likelihood interval are implausible values of in light of the observed data
  • Values of outside a 1% likelihood interval are very implausible values of in light of the observed data
